  "market_context": "On the ES 1-hour, the analyst illustrates a schematic consolidation range with buyside liquidity at 3979.0 (range high) and sellside liquidity at 3890.0 (range low), used to demonstrate the box setup logic before showing live examples.",
  "key_observation": "The box setup requires an aggressive deviation out of the range high or low and an equally aggressive move back into the range, which forms the wick on a higher time frame and sets up the retest entry.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Mark the consolidation range using the bodies, identifying the range high at 3979.0 as buyside liquidity and the range low at 3890.0 as sellside liquidity.",
    "Step 2: Wait for price to leave the range, looking for an aggressive deviation above the range high (or below the range low).",
    "Step 3: Require the move back into the range to also be aggressive, since this is what forms the wick on the higher time frame.",
    "Step 4: Plan a short entry on the retest of the deviation/old high, with stop placed on the current high of the deviation.",
    "Step 5: Target the opposite side of the range (sellside liquidity at the range low) and any liquidity resting beyond it.",
    "Step 6: Frame the structure as Power of 3 — the range as accumulation, the deviation as manipulation, and the move toward the opposite liquidity as distribution."
  ],
  "outcome": null,
  "lessons": "A valid box setup requires both the move out of the range and the move back in to be aggressive; this forms a higher time frame wick and enables a clean retest entry with stop on the deviation high and target at opposite liquidity.",
